\begin_layout Standard
[Variation in conditions] The study inspects how consumption varies in a
 developing economy with respect to the differences in prosperity both within
 a geographical reference area and across geographical areas spread through
 the economy.
 We consider that any improvement in prosperity for the consumer in a certain
 area of reference is contingent on her occupational or educational status,
 her inheritable wealth and the positive externality (or affluence) associated
 with being in the area of reference itself.
 Since a consumer better equipped with educational or occupational status
 and a social network of more richer consumers is - all else being the same
 - better prepared for higher prosperity, the study contrasts the educational
 and occupational expenditures against the consumption on assets (durable
 goods) and non-durable consumption across Nigeria and Tanzania.
 The comparison across the two economies essentially tracks the consumer's
 preparedness to be in a improved surrounding area as the educational and
 occupational expenditure against the current consumer characteristics -
 including the educational, occupational levels as well as the assets owned
 by the consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[cui bono] Such a comparison of consumption against consumer characteristics
 is of interest for two reasons.
 First, such consumer characteristics have a role to play in the appeal
 for mobility and relative income since a consumer with a certain level
 of needs, assets and educational/occupational level would not be indifferent
 being in a poorer reference with less relative poverty.
 In other words, a desire for relative prosperity may be outpaced by extreme
 differences in reference areas.
 Second, the distribution of educational and occupational skills across
 the economy could in turn determine the access to consumer markets in the
 economy and could also influence the quality of consumption directly.
 A control for inequality in prosperity across across geographical reference
 thus helps us better understand how consumption may differs within an economy
 and across multiple economies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[status consumption, migration] We believe that these two features of an
 economy would have implications for both migration pressures and the notions
 of status consumption in an economy.
 While we don't elaborate on these within the current chapter, the consumers
 preference to remain in a poorer reference while enjoying relative affluence
 needs to be qualified in light of extremely sparse distribution of economic
 opportunities in the economy (see literature on migration).
 More particularly, when a poorer reference may have less opportunities
 both for mobility and status consumption, then the escape to a richer reference
 may promise an access to improbable mobilities for the consumer - rather
 than merely the opportunity to improve her income in the near-term.
\end_layout

