\begin_layout Standard
The goal of the current chapter is consider the role of asset and occupational
 disparities on consumption by incorporating the prosperity level associated
 with a certain reference into the consumer choice.
 The levels of prosperity are determined with the long-term assets within
 the boundary of the geographical reference area and the consumer is expected
 to balance i) having some relative prosperity while in her reference with
 ii) getting prepared to be in an area of higher prosperity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an environment of severe income inequalities in a developing, one would
 observe both that certain geographical areas are poorer than others and
 that there are extreme income differences within the population of a geographic
al area of reference.
 With a reference-bound utility, therefore, consumer can be said to select
 a particular area of prosperity by optimising the utility she achieves
 from i) being in the reference area of a certain prosperity itself ii)
 achieving a high expenditure relative to the consumption level in the reference
 and iii) improving chances to be in an area of higher prosperity and therefore
 of positive externality (simultaneously increasing her chances to have
 a higher income).
\end_layout

