\begin_layout Standard
A possible issue with the above approach is that the social identities may
 operate in parallel with the effect of disparity across the geographical
 areas of reference.
 Ignoring the social identities in the above comparison of consumption may
 thus result in an omitted variable bias if the social identities have the
 same effect on the consumer's prosperity as the externality of being in
 a particular area of reference.
 That said, however, such a social identity (race, religion or other) must
 both be observed at a wider level across all the geographical areas of
 reference and have a direct influence on the consumer's prosperity for
 the bias to be significant.
 While we do consider the controls corresponding to religious affiliation
 and linguistic preferences in the two economies, we also don't find no
 evidence for a significant political disadvantage to a specific social
 identity in either Nigeria and Tanzania.
 Therefore, while social identities may have a role to play at the finer
 levels within the geographical area of reference, their role across all
 the geographic areas need not be more significant than the controls of
 prosperity and geographical disparities.
 Consumer societies in sub-Saharan Africa - much like elsewhere - are after
 all organised around clans or social groups, but the effect of reference
 levels implied by such micro-identities may not be significant if the diverse
 identities are dispersed over the wider geographical extent and do not
 form a separate social group with a direct disadvantage to prosperity.
 More specifically, if the communities within a geographical area are not
 related to the communities within another geographical area, then the effects
 of different reference levels in the two areas due to respective variegated
 social identities are dominated by the disparities in prosperity and income.
\end_layout

